[World Meningitis Day] The theme for World Meningitis Day 2018 is #AllMeningitisMatters . The campaign will focus on the different causes of meningitis and the vaccines that can help protect against certain strains of bacterial and viral meningitis .
The key messages of the 2018 campaign are: 1. Meningitis is a potentially deadly disease that can kill within 24 hours. 2. Bacterial meningitis can be caused by many different types of bacteria.

As not all strains of #meningitis are vaccine preventable, being able to recognise the symptoms is crucial! Learn the symptoms to mark this year’s World Meningitis Day! #AllMeningitisMatters pic.twitter.com/Y3eqsIp5S5
The common strains of meningitis disease include the meningococcal meningitis types A, C, W and Y. They are all vaccine preventable.
Conjugate meningitis vaccines are different from polysaccharide meningitis vaccines as they provide much higher and sustainable levels of protection against the disease.
Speak to your local health care provider to find out which meningitis vaccines are available to you. Not all meningitis vaccines provide protection against all strains of the disease.
Even with prompt diagnosis and treatment, around 10-20% of patients of bacterial meningitis will die within 24 to 48 hours after the onset of symptoms.
170,000 deaths are caused annually by bacterial meningitis . Currently available vaccines could prevent more than 90% of cases of bacterial meningitis .
Ear infections can lead to meningitis , brain abscess and other neurological complications. http:// zpr.io/nw55p
Each year over 1 million people are affected by Meningitis . Infants and children under 5 years old and adolescents between 15 and 19 years of age are most at risk.

Por fortuna, en nuestro medio, las meningitis causadas por bacterias solo son 5-10 de cada 100. Es decir que es mucho más probable una meningitis por un virus que por una bacteria. pic.twitter.com/KhNqsaoqDQ
Las baterías que provocan meningitis son casi siempre dos: el Neumococo y el Meningococo.

Las causadas por bacterias son las llamadas “ meningitis malas” xq pueden dejar graves secuelas y causar la muerte. Son las q realmente nos preocupan a los pediatras. Por fortuna suelen solucionarse con tratamiento antibiótico y una vigilancia estrecha, generalmente en la UCI.

A las causadas por virus se las conoce como “ meningitis buenas” ya que se curan sin tratamiento, aunque a veces al niño hay que ingresarle para controlar el dolor y los vómitos. pic.twitter.com/ukirkg3heL

Las meningitis son una enfermedad que provoca la inflamación de las meninges. Las meninges son las cubiertas que envuelven al cerebro. La causa suele ser infecciosa: virus o baterías. pic.twitter.com/Wfaz4yXtCG
